&lt;h2 id=&#34;map&#34;&gt;Map
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/p/batworthy-and-chagford-common/map.jpg&#34;
	width=&#34;1000&#34;
	height=&#34;746&#34;
	srcset=&#34;http://localhost:1313/p/batworthy-and-chagford-common/map_hu_77dba7aa263ee795.jpg 480w, http://localhost:1313/p/batworthy-and-chagford-common/map_hu_a23d428c383aa926.jpg 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
		alt=&#34;Map of Route -  Crown Copyright -  Ordnance Survey Licence number 100047373&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;134&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;321px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;introduction&#34;&gt;Introduction
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;The area around Batworthy is unusually rich in ancient history, even for Dartmoor. Even though this walk is relatively short, and has only gentle inclines, we&amp;rsquo;ll encounter a lot of bronze age remains, starting with one of the best and largest hut circles on the moor. There&amp;rsquo;s also two tors included, one of which has some very well formed rock basins.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We include some driving directions, although a Satnav will generally find the way.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;routing-box&#34;&gt;
  &lt;div class=&#34;routing-header&#34;&gt;
    &lt;img src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/icons/signpost.svg&#34;
       alt=&#34;&#34;
       class=&#34;routing-icon&#34;&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div class=&#34;routing-content&#34;&gt;
    &lt;em&gt;When you&amp;rsquo;re ready to leave, walk back along the approach road for 350m until you encounter the large hutcircle on the left&lt;/em&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;round-pound&#34;&gt;Round Pound
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/p/batworthy-and-chagford-common/1.jpg&#34;
	width=&#34;1909&#34;
	height=&#34;750&#34;
	srcset=&#34;http://localhost:1313/p/batworthy-and-chagford-common/1_hu_4c8b383627060c6d.jpg 480w, http://localhost:1313/p/batworthy-and-chagford-common/1_hu_fe3e686a4c7973f7.jpg 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
		alt=&#34;Round Pound&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;254&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;610px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Round Pound enclosure and hut circles at SX 6638 8684.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The pound contains a central hut that was excavated in 1951 and 1952 by Lady Fox who found Iron Age artefacts, as well as a Bronze Age flint arrowhead. The pound is described J. Butler (1991), Dartmoor Atlas of Antiquities  II, 36.1 Kes Tor settlement, pages 170-176.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;link&#34; href=&#34;https://www.heritagegateway.org.uk/Gateway/Results_Single.aspx?uid=MDV6117&amp;amp;resourceID=104&#34;  target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;
    &gt;HER Devon &amp;amp; Dartmoor NDV6117 - Roundy Pound, Gidleigh&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;from-warren-house-inn-towards-moretonhampstead&#34;&gt;From Warren House Inn (towards Moretonhampstead)
&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Take 1st road on LEFT – route to Fernworthy&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Pass Jurston Farm&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Yellands Crossroads – TURN LEFT&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Pass left turn to Lower Corndon&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Pass right turn &amp;hellip;..&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Take HAIRPIN LEFT to Fernworthy - use the layby to turn the car!&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Pass a left turn to Higher Corndon&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Take RIGHT turn and pass Collihole Farm, Hole Farm and Cullaton to T-junction, turn LEFT to THORN&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Pass THORN and go to YEO FARM&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;At Yeo Farm bear RIGHT to TEIGNCOMBE&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Drive through Teigncombe to the end of the road&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The end-of-the-road car park is marked with the yellow cross.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;parking&#34;&gt;Parking
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;There is a small parking area at the given coordinates. The approach roads to Batworthy are quite long and narrow, although rarely busy.&lt;/p&gt;
